@segment
How Objects Speak
HOS

@package
Why Won't This Door Open?
Free
# @text, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant C (3 stories), default intro, teaching: affordances

@text
Most everyday objects were made by someone who never met the user.
A hand picks one up, eyes glance at it, and a guess happens before any thought.
Sometimes the guess is right.
Sometimes the body pulls a handle that was supposed to be pushed.

@text
Ravi approaches a glass door with a vertical metal handle on each side.
His hand wraps around the bar and pulls.
The door does not move.
He pulls again, harder, and the door still does not budge.
A small sticker near the hinge says PUSH.
Once he pushes instead of pulls, the door opens easily.

@text
A kettle sits on a stove, full and steaming, with a smooth wooden curve as a handle.
The hand reaches for the curve without checking.
The fingers wrap, the wrist lifts, and the kettle pours into the cup.
Nobody read the manual. Nobody had to.
The shape is the same as a hundred other kettles in a hundred other kitchens.
Lifting it was already a familiar move.

@text
Sofia steps into a hotel shower in a city far from home.
A single chrome ring sits on the wall, with no labels and no arrows.
She turns it left, and ice-cold water arrives.
She turns it right, and ice-cold water arrives again.
Then the ring is pushed inward, and warm water finally appears.
The sequence took 2 minutes, in a room that should have taken zero.

@question
Why did the wooden kettle handle work without a single label?

answer: The label was hidden underneath the curve.
consequence: Nothing was hidden. The handle worked because its shape already showed what to do.

answer: The shape matched a thousand other kettle handles the hand had lifted before.
consequence: The shape was familiar from memory, and lifting was already the obvious move.

answer: Kettles are simpler than doors and showers.
consequence: Many doors are simpler than that kettle. Simplicity is not what saved it. The shape was.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A familiar shape lets the hand know what to do without any thought.
hint: The hand had already met that shape on hundreds of other kettles.

@text
In the kitchen, the wooden curve had already shown what to do before the hand moved.
The shape itself can already say how to use the object.
This is called an <c:g>affordance</c:g>, the first way a designed object speaks to the user.
A kettle handle affords lifting, a flat plate affords pushing, and a vertical bar affords pulling.
When the shape matches the action, the object disappears into the work.

@true_false
A kettle handle shaped like a smooth wooden curve already shows the hand what to do with it.

true: True
consequence: The shape lets the hand act without waiting for any label.

false: False
consequence: The wooden curve was the entire instruction. No words were needed.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: A familiar handle shape carries the action inside it, and the hand reacts before the eyes do.
hint: A kettle is rarely lifted by reading a manual first.

@reflect
A door that resisted before the right way was guessed.
A handle that fit the hand on the first reach.
A control panel that needed three glances before the first action.

@text
Some objects show their use right on the surface, while others hide it behind a flat panel.
The shape is only one of the cues an object can give.
Beyond it, small visible signs decide where the hand goes when the shape stays silent.

@package
Quiet Cues
# @quote, @text, @text, @true_false, @text, @text
# Variant A (2 scenes), quote intro, teaching: signifiers

@quote
Affordances determine what actions are possible. Signifiers communicate where the action should take place.
Donald A. Norman

@text
Imagine standing in front of an elevator panel inside a tall office building.
Two metal arrows point up and down, with a small light behind one of them.
The finger reaches without thinking, and the up arrow is pressed.
There is no instruction, no voice, no manual to consult.
The arrow itself was the message, and the light underneath confirmed it.
Five seconds later, the right car is on its way.

@text
Picture the same kind of glass door as a moment ago, the one with the metal handle.
A small flat plate has been added at chest height, where a hand naturally lands.
The plate is brushed steel, the size of a postcard, with no words on it.
The plate has nothing to grip and nothing to pull.
The hand pushes, because pushing is the only thing the plate offers.
This time the door opens at once.

@true_false
A flat metal plate on a glass door tells the hand to push without using a single word.

true: True
consequence: The plate has nothing to grip, so pushing is the only thing it can mean.

false: False
consequence: The flat shape already says push, even with no word printed on it.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The plate is a pure visual sign. Its shape rules out pulling, so only pushing is left.
hint: Consider what the plate offers to the fingers compared to a vertical handle.

@text
On the elevator panel, the arrow on the wall did more than allow a press.
It told the finger exactly where to press.
The flat plate on the door did the same job for the open hand.
A small visible sign that points to the right place is called a <c:g>signifier</c:g>.
This is the second way a designed object speaks to the user.

@text
Most well-made objects use a shape and a sign together.
Even with both in place, an object can still confuse if it answers the wrong question.
The third part of the vocabulary is about how a control lines up with what it actually moves.

@package
Before the Hand Moves
# @text, @text, @text, @pause, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant D (3 stories), skip intro, teaching: natural mapping

@text
Yuki has a four-burner stove in a small apartment kitchen.
Two knobs are on the left, two on the right, but the burners are arranged in a square.
A pot of water sits on the front-right burner, steam beginning to rise.
She reaches for the front-right knob and turns it.
The back-left burner clicks on instead, and the heat is wasted on empty air.
Yuki checks the small diagram by the knobs and turns each one until the right burner glows.

@text
A meeting room has three light switches in a row by the door.
The ceiling has two lamp panels at the front and one over the table.
Nothing on the switches says which is which.
The first person in the morning flips the leftmost switch and the table light comes on.
The second flips the middle, and one of the front panels joins.
The third gives up and turns on all three.

@text
Marek's small car turns onto a quiet country road at dusk.
He eases the wheel a quarter to the left, and the car drifts left in the lane.
A second turn, sharper and to the right, and the car answers the same way.
Marek did not have to think about which direction the wheel matched on the road.
A wheel that turned right when spun left would have ended the trip on the first corner.
For 100 years, this match has been so reliable nobody calls it design at all.

@pause
In a well-built cockpit, the levers for the landing gear are sometimes shaped like tiny wheels.

@text
On the stove, the knobs and the burners did not match, and the cook had to translate every meal.
On the country road, the wheel and the road matched, and no translation was needed.
A control that lines up with what it moves is using <c:g>natural mapping</c:g>.
This is the third way a designed object speaks to the user.
When the layout of the knobs mirrors the burners, no labels are needed at all.

@true_false
On a four-burner stove, knobs arranged in a square that mirrors the burners need fewer labels to work.

true: True
consequence: The shape of the layout already shows which knob goes with which burner.

false: False
consequence: A square arrangement that mirrors the burners removes most of the need for labels.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: When controls share the layout of what they control, the hand reads the position instead of the text.
hint: A label is rarely needed when the position itself gives the answer.

@reflect
A control that always seems to need a glance at its label first.
A familiar steering wheel that has not surprised the driver in years.
A volume dial whose direction was learned once and never misread again.

@text
Shape, sign, and layout work together to let an object speak before the hand moves.
What happens in the moment after the hand acts is its own kind of message.
An object that goes silent right after a press leaves the user guessing.

@package
What the Click Should Have Said...
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant B (2 beats), misconception intro, teaching: feedback

@text
Most people assume an object's job is to <c:r>do the work in silence</c:r>.
A button is pressed, and the rest is the machine's problem.
But silence after a press is also a message.
A silent machine and a broken machine look the same to the user.

@text
At the end of a long day, Akira stands in a small kitchen with dishes stacked next to a microwave.
A bowl of soup is placed inside, and the door closes with a soft thud.
The 1-minute button is pressed, and a tiny green dot lights on the panel.
A faint hum begins behind the metal wall, and the timer counts down in pale digits.
Akira turns away, knowing the soup will arrive in about a minute.

@text
Now picture the same kitchen with a different microwave, where the panel sits dark after the press.
There is no light, no sound, no number on the screen.
Akira waits 10 seconds, then 20, then taps the door.
Maybe it is heating, maybe the press did not register, maybe the bowl is going cold.
Without a single signal, every second of waiting is a guess.

@question
Why did the second microwave feel broken even when nothing inside had actually failed?

answer: A microwave with no display is always broken on the inside.
consequence: Nothing was wrong inside the second machine. The lack of a signal made it feel wrong.

answer: Without any signal back, Akira could not know the press had been received.
consequence: The press might have worked. With no light or sound to confirm it, Akira had to guess.

answer: Akira pressed too gently for the button to register.
consequence: Whether the press registered or not, Akira could not tell, and that was the problem.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A signal back from the machine turns a press into a confirmed action.
hint: The first kitchen had proof the machine was working, the second had only silence.

@text
The hum, the dot, and the counting digits told Akira the machine had heard the press.
A signal back from the object after an action is called <c:g>feedback</c:g>.
This is the fourth way a designed object speaks to the user.
Without feedback, a working microwave can look the same as a broken one.
With feedback, even a long heating cycle feels short.

@true_false
A microwave that hums and shows a timer feels faster than one that goes silent for the same minute.

true: True
consequence: A visible signal turns a wait into a confirmed countdown, even when the time is identical.

false: False
consequence: The two minutes feel different because one is filled with proof of work.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: The clock measures the same minute, but the hand and the eyes do not.
hint: Compare a minute watching numbers count down with a minute watching a dark panel.

@text
Affordance, signifier, mapping, and feedback are four ways an object can speak to the user.
When all four show up, the object disappears into the work.
What happens, though, when the user already carries the wrong picture of how the object works?

@segment
Where Design Fails
WDF

@package
The Object Has a Story
# @text, @text, @text, @text, @question, @text, @true_false, @text
# Variant C (3 stories), default intro, teaching: conceptual models

@text
Every object that anyone has ever picked up came with a story.
The story is what the user thinks the object is doing inside, when no one is watching.
Sometimes the story matches what really happens.
Often it does not, and the gap is where every small problem begins.

@text
A refrigerator hums in the corner of Mira's kitchen, with two dials on a panel inside.
One dial says FRESH FOOD, the other says FREEZER, and both run from 1 to 7.
A summer week comes along, the milk turns sour faster, and Mira turns the FRESH FOOD dial to 7.
Three days later the freezer is over-icing, and the fridge compartment is barely cool.
The two dials seem to control two separate cabinets, but they really control one cooling unit and a valve.
The picture in Mira's head was wrong, and the food spoiled.

@text
Hassan's small house gets cold around 4pm in October.
The thermostat reads 16 degrees, and his hand turns it all the way up to 30.
Heat will arrive faster this way, Hassan thinks, the way water arrives faster from a fully open tap.
But the heater is either on or off, and 30 will heat the room no faster than 22 would.
By the time the room is warm, it is too warm, and the window has to be opened.

@text
A hotel elevator has a close-door button next to the floor numbers.
Lena, late for a meeting, presses it 5 times before the doors begin to slide together.
The pressing felt like progress, and the speed felt like a result.
In most modern elevators, the button is wired to do nothing for a public passenger.
The doors closed on the same timer they would have closed on without a finger near them.

@question
Why does a working object become a daily problem when the user's picture of it is wrong?

answer: The user presses the right control in the wrong way.
consequence: The user acts on the picture in the head. Every press matches a story that is not really happening.

answer: The inside of the machine breaks over time.
consequence: The fridge and the heater worked exactly as built. The user's expectations were the only problem.

answer: The user should have read the manual more carefully.
consequence: Reading the manual once would not help. The wrong story survives in the head after the words fade.

correct_answers: 1
explanation: Every action follows the picture in the head, even when the picture is wrong.
hint: Consider what Mira believed about the fridge versus what the fridge actually does.

@text
Each person had a different picture of how the object worked inside.
Mira pictured two cabinets, Hassan a tap, and Lena a button speaking to a door.
This picture in the user's head is called a <c:g>conceptual model</c:g>.
It is the fifth way a designed object meets the user.
When the picture is wrong, every press follows a story the object never confirmed.

@true_false
Pressing a thermostat from 16 to 30 will warm a room faster than pressing it to 22.

true: True
consequence: The heater is either on or off, and 30 produces no faster a warm-up than 22.

false: False
consequence: The heater runs at one speed, no matter the number on the dial.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: The user's tap-style picture does not match an on-or-off heater.
hint: Most heaters have only one running speed, no slow setting and no fast setting.

@text
A wrong story inside the head turns a working object into a daily small fight.
There is, though, a kind of object built to refuse the wrong story altogether.

@package
1 Move That Cannot Fail
# @true_false, @text, @text, @question, @text, @reflect, @text
# Variant E (2 mechanisms), true/false intro, teaching: forcing functions

@true_false
A bank machine that keeps the card in the slot until the cash is pulled out is poor design.

true: True
consequence: The reversed order looks like extra friction, but it forces the user to take both cash and card.

false: False
consequence: The reversed order ended a quiet daily mistake, where someone walks away with cash but no card.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Holding the card hostage until the cash is taken is a step that quietly removes a common error.
hint: Think about which item used to be left behind at older bank machines.

@text
A modern car has a small chain that ties the gas cap to the fuel door.
The cap cannot be set down on the roof, where it would be forgotten.
At the pump, the cap is unscrewed, the nozzle goes in, and the cap dangles by its tether.
There is no way to drive off without first noticing the cap and screwing it back on.
The driver does not have to remember the cap. The car remembers it on their behalf.

@text
Older bank machines gave out cash first and the card second.
A person in a rush would take the cash, turn away, and leave the card behind.
Newer machines flipped the order. The card is returned first, then the cash.
The user cannot walk away without the card, because the card is back in the wallet first.
A change in the order of two steps removed a common mistake from millions of cash machines.

@question
How does a tethered gas cap remove an error without telling the driver anything?

answer: It locks the fuel door until the cap is back in place.
consequence: The cap is just the visible reminder. The driver does the closing themselves.

answer: It refuses to let the cap leave the car, so forgetting it becomes physically impossible.
consequence: The chain ties the cap to the car. Wherever the driver is, the cap is too.

answer: It alerts the driver with a beep when the cap is open.
consequence: A beep can be ignored. The chain cannot. The mechanism works without a sound.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: A forgotten cap is no longer possible if the cap cannot leave the car at all.
hint: Notice what is physically tying the cap to the body of the car.

@text
The chain on the cap and the new order at the bank machine do the same job.
Each one only allows the next correct action and blocks every wrong one.
This kind of design is called a <c:g>forcing function</c:g>.
It is the sixth way a designed object meets the user.
The cap cannot be forgotten because the cap cannot leave the car.

@reflect
A small object that used to be left behind, on a counter or in a coat pocket.
A door that requires the lights off before it will close, in a darkroom or a fridge.
A tool whose order of steps has been redesigned to remove a single common mistake.

@text
A forcing function takes the wrong move off the table before the user can choose it.
But not every error can be designed away in advance.
A small story remains, about who really gets blamed when the object and the hand do not agree.

@package
Bad Day, Worse Design
# @text, @text, @text, @question, @pause, @text, @true_false, @reflect, @text
# Variant D (3 stories), skip intro, teaching: design error

@text
Tomas's small kitchen settles into a Tuesday morning.
The toaster has a dial labelled 1 to 6 and a button marked START.
He sets the dial to 4, presses the button, and 2 minutes later a smoke alarm is screaming.
Tomas blames himself for not paying attention, opens a window, and writes a note: be more careful.
But the dial never explained that 4 was meant for two thin slices of white bread.
The dense whole-grain he brought home this morning needed a different number.

@text
Linnea has to take a pill once in the morning and once at night, in two different doses.
The two bottles look almost identical, the labels are dense, and she is sleepy at 10pm.
She opens the wrong bottle, and the morning dose is swallowed at night.
Linnea calls herself careless, sets a louder alarm, and tries again the next day.
The label was 8 lines of small print on a curved white surface, in a dim kitchen.

@text
On an airplane, a flight attendant has to demonstrate the seat belt every flight.
The reason is that the seat belt is not the kind found in any car the passengers know.
A car belt clicks in and unclicks with a button.
An airplane belt has a metal tongue that has to be lifted, not pressed.
Every wrong attempt has been blamed on the passenger, year after year.
But the same belt has fooled the same kind of person on every flight for decades.

@question
What do the toaster, the pill bottle, and the seat belt have in common after the mistake?

answer: A user who agrees the mistake was their own fault.
consequence: Each user did blame themselves first. But the same blame appears in every kitchen and every airplane.

answer: An object whose design quietly invited the same mistake from many different people.
consequence: The object is the common factor. The same error happens across countless hands and homes.

answer: A clear sign that the user should have read the manual.
consequence: Most people do not read manuals for toasters or seat belts. The design has to work without them.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: When the same error appears across thousands of users, the cause is the object, not the people.
hint: Look at what is identical across all three scenes after the mistake.

@pause
The flight attendant who shows the seat belt every day has watched the same confusion appear for years.

@text
On the toaster, the pill bottle, and the seat belt, the same mistake repeats across many users.
When the same error appears on the same object, the cause is in the object, not the user.
This is called a <c:g>design error</c:g>, the seventh and final way a designed object meets the user.
A failure that keeps happening to many people is rarely a personal failure to pay attention.
The first six pieces show the user what to do, and the seventh decides who carries the blame.

@true_false
A seat belt that confuses passengers flight after flight is best understood as a problem with the passengers.

true: True
consequence: After thousands of confused passengers on the same belt, the common factor is the belt.

false: False
consequence: A confusion shared by millions on the same object is a fact about the object first.

correct_answers: 2
explanation: Repeated identical errors across very different users point to the design, not the user.
hint: Notice which side of the scene has been identical for decades.

@reflect
A small daily mistake that has been quietly blamed on personal carelessness for years.
A common confusion that shows up on the same object, across many different hands.
A button or a switch whose error rate stays the same regardless of who is pressing it.

@text
Affordance, signifier, mapping, feedback, conceptual model, forcing function, and a fair look at blame.
These seven pieces decide whether an object disappears into the work or quietly resists every user.
When an everyday object resists next time, which of the seven was missing, and was anyone really at fault?
